            "contentString": "{patientName} was diagnosed with Parkinson's disease at age 73, following an evaluation by a movement disorder neurologist after his primary care physician noted the resting tremor and right-arm rigidity. He was initially started on a dopamine agonist with good symptomatic response, and levodopa was introduced approximately 18 months later as motor symptoms progressed.\n\nHis past medical history is significant for hypertension diagnosed at age 60, managed with medication, and type 2 diabetes mellitus diagnosed at age 65, currently controlled with oral agents. He has a history of benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH) causing urinary hesitancy and nocturia, managed conservatively. He experienced a transient ischemic attack (TIA) at age 70 with no residual deficits, after which antiplatelet therapy was initiated.\n\n{patientName} was hospitalized once at age 76 following a fall at home that resulted in a right femoral neck fracture requiring surgical repair. He underwent formal physical and occupational therapy rehabilitation post-operatively and has since used a quad cane for ambulation. He has also received speech therapy for hypophonia and dysphagia.\n\nHe has a 20 pack-year smoking history (pipe smoking, ceased in his early 50s) and drinks one small glass of red wine occasionally. He has no history of illicit drug use. His neuropsychological assessment from last year revealed mild cognitive impairment with deficits in executive function and visuospatial processing. He has a documented allergy to sulfonamide antibiotics and shellfish."
